answers.body_markdown:
If you can use strdup, that implies your strings have no zero-bytes in them.

If your strings have no zero-bytes in them, you can replace the `char**` with a `char*` and a single large allocation with a zero-byte between each string and a `size_t` in the struct to indicate the length [1]. This makes the implementation *slightly* more clunky at both ends but (1) easier to conceptually understand, (2) more cache efficient, (3) easier to clean up, as all the deallocations can be replaced with a single call to `free` on your `char*`

[1] you might naively use two sequential zero-bytes to indicate the end of the string, but that would prevent you from having empty strings

    extern &quot;C&quot;
    {
        struct MyCustomStruct
        {
            char *text;
            size_t textLength;
        };

        MyCustomStruct getMyCustomStructInstance()
        {
            std::vector&lt;std::string&gt; lines{&quot;abc&quot;, &quot;xyz&quot;};

            size_t textLength = 0;

            for (auto const &amp;line : lines)
            {
                textLength += line.size()+1;
                            // the +1 is a magic constant here that indicates the
                            // presence of the null-byte at the end of each string
                            // you may want to do it differently so it doesn&#39;t
                            // just hang out here to confuse future readers
                            //  - A comment is possible, of course, but perhaps
                            //  not the best approach.
            }

            if (textLength == 0)
            {
                // some of these C functions don&#39;t handle edge cases
                // with zero-allocations so we&#39;re out immediately
                return MyCustomStruct{nulltpr, 0};
            }

            char *text = (char *)malloc(textLength);

            if (!text)
            {
                // insert your favorite error handling. For preference,
                // I would change the return type to
                // std::optional&lt;MyCustomStruct&gt; and do &quot;return {};&quot;
                // but you could also throw an exception here.
            }

            // At this point, the solution diverse, depending on how
            // performance sensitive you are. If you can accept two buffers
            //  (which I think you can, given the many strdup&#39;s you were
            //  willing to accept) I would do this:

            {
                std::string all_strings;
                all_strings.reserve(textLength);
                for (auto const &amp;line : lines)
                {
                    all_strings += line;
                    all_strings += &quot;\0&quot;;
                }
                std::copy(all_strings.begin(), all_strings.end(), text);

                return MyCustomStruct{text, textLength};
            }

            // If you are very performance sensitive here, I would instead:
            {
                auto next_string = text;

                for (auto const &amp;line : lines)
                {
                    std::copy(line.begin(), line.end, next_string);
                    *next_string = &#39;\0&#39;;
                    ++next_string;
                }

                return MyCustomStruct{text, textLength};
            }
        }
    }

NB: Obviously if you throw from this, or return a `std::optional`, you are no longer a good C function. I would probably make a pure C++ function for the logic, and then a pure C function that calls the C++ function and handles whatever error it might return in C parlance, e.g. like this:

    MyCustomStruct myCustomStruct;
    int result = fillMyCustomStruct(&amp;myCustomStruct);
    if(result != FillResult_Ok)
        //etc.

